Time Complexity:

Let n = number of nodes in linked list

    Detecting cycle (slow & fast pointers) → O(n)
    Finding start of cycle → O(n)

Overall: O(n)


Space Complexity:

    No extra space used (only pointers)

Overall: O(1)


Approach:

1. Initialize two pointers:
   - slow → moves 1 step
   - fast → moves 2 steps

2. Traverse the list:
   - Move slow by 1 and fast by 2
   - If they meet → cycle exists

3. If fast reaches null:
   - No cycle → return null

4. If cycle is detected:
   - Move fast pointer to head

5. Now move both slow and fast one step at a time:
   - The point where they meet again is the start of the cycle

6. Return that node








/**
 * Definition for singly-linked list.
 * class ListNode {
 *     int val;
 *     ListNode next;
 *     ListNode(int x) {
 *         val = x;
 *         next = null;
 *     }
 * }
 */
public class Solution {
    public ListNode detectCycle(ListNode head) {
        ListNode slow = head;
        ListNode fast = head;
        while(fast!=null && fast.next!=null){
            slow=slow.next;
            fast=fast.next.next;
            if(slow==fast) break;
        }
        if(fast==null || fast.next==null) return null;
        fast=head;
        while(fast!=slow){
            fast=fast.next;
            slow=slow.next;
        }
        return slow;
    }
}
